      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the earlier slip-up; I was merely trying to inject a bit of whimsical flavor, though I must admit, the idea of a \"goblin-esque\" circle is a bit of a stretch, as goblins are usually more prone to linear mischief than circular geometry. However, to answer your question directly and stick strictly to the academic facts you requested:\n\nOn the flat side of the Circle of Fifths, you move counter-clockwise from C Major. The order of the added flats is **B♭, E♭, A♭, D♭, G♭, C♭, F♭**.\n\nHere is the breakdown:\n*   **1 Flat:** B♭ Major\n*   **2 Flats:** E♭ Major\n*   **3 Flats:** A♭ Major\n*   **4 Flats:** D♭ Major\n*   **5 Flats:** G♭ Major\n*   **6 Flats:** C♭ Major\n*   **7 Flats:** F♭ Major\n\nYou can remember this order by the mnemonic \"Boys Eat Apple, Don't Get Candy\" (B, E, A, D, G",
